# Prefer Named Exports

Use named exports instead of `export default`.

- **Refactoring**: Easier to rename and find references; IDEs and tools work better with named symbols.
- **Consistency**: Import sites always use the same name as the export; no arbitrary local names.
- **Re-exports**: Named exports compose cleanly when re-exporting from barrels.

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid
export default function VerificationCodeEmail({ code }: Props) {
  return <Html>...</Html>;
}

// ✅ Prefer
export function VerificationCodeEmail({ code }: Props) {
  return <Html>...</Html>;
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid
import VerificationCodeEmail from "./VerificationCodeEmail";

// ✅ Prefer
import { VerificationCodeEmail } from "./VerificationCodeEmail";
```

Only use default export when a framework or tool requires it (e.g. Next.js pages, some React Email preview setups).
